Lifestyle 

Etsy's Kristina Salen

The Etsy CFO has a big e-commerce job. Here's how she manages her work and life.



posted Apr 21st, 2014 at 3:19pm 









 




 Comments 











Kristina Salen



Kristina Salen and her husband, Daniel Bernstein, live in Brooklyn, NY, with kids Jules, 11, and Arlo, 8.
My Job
As CFO since last year of an online marketplace with one million vendors of handmade goods, my job is to help others do. I’m a strategic therapist. I listen to my colleagues, listen for opportunities, hear their problems and help them prioritize. A CFO’s job is really to enable growth over a multi-year period, to help determine whether plans will sustain growth. My day is filled with meetings: with our head of global facilities to talk about 10-year real estate plans, then with our chief technical officer, then with our VP of international to talk about a global challenge. I work with 500 passionate people in a mission-driven company with a strong sense of purpose. We believe we’re reimagining commerce. We’re a model that will create a more fulfilling and connected world that goes beyond price and convenience— creating a real connection between our 30 million active buyers and our sellers.
**
How Work Life Works**
Not so well over the past year. I started this new job in a new field and moved my family from Boston to New York City, meaning a lot of change and long hours and massive to-do lists. It’s been chaos, and challenging to find calm in the storm, but it’s okay as long as we all take deep breaths. My husband is a partner in the fullest sense—we only allow ourselves one freak-out at a time. He’s been a stay-at-home dad for a decade, and it hasn’t always been easy. He’s the point person on pretty much everything kids and home, so the burden is lifted from me. I do the laundry because I like to. And since I travel a fair amount, I do everything I can do from my phone at the airport.
Staying Connected
I travel one or two months out of the year. Otherwise, it’s a real gift that I see my kids every morning. I make sure they’re dressed, have breakfast and are out the door with Daniel. I get home a little after 6 and get dinner on and do kid stuff and then go back online at 9 p.m. I go in to work late on Fridays—when I have the luxury of walking my kids to school. I take them to ballet classes and drum lessons on the weekends. It’s about the little consistent things: walking to school, cuddling on the couch, waking the boys with kisses.
Family Time
It’s dinnertime, nearly every night. My husband is a trained chef, and that’s lucky. We talk about all kinds of stuff: school, big-picture issues like why dogs and cats have to be neutered, whatever comes up. On weekends, with the kids’ classes and all, we focus on nighttimes. We have movie night—recently it was Raiders of the Lost Ark. We like to have other families over for dinner. We set the table nicely with place cards. It’s a family date night for everyone. As for date night with my husband, our regular one fell away with the demands of my new job and our new home, but once a month we go out to dinner or do something. By September we should be through the transition.
In My Bag

A mess, usually
Macbook Air
A drawing by Arlo
A lucky necklace Jules made in preschool
A cosmetic bag full of lipsticks I never wear
A ton of old receipts and to-do lists
A pinecone or crab claw seasonally

My Favorite Things
Listening to cheesy Top 40 music, getting dressed up (and reliving the prom), reading medieval crime noir (like The Name of the Rose).
—As told to Barbara Turvett
 






